Linear regression
We have recently seen models that look like \[
\begin{align}
y_i &\sim N(\mu_i, \sigma) \\
\mu_i &= \alpha_i + \beta x_i
\end{align}
\] Or (using another notation) \[
\begin{align}
y_i &= \alpha_i + \beta x_i + \epsilon_i \\
\epsilon_i &\sim N(0, \sigma)
\end{align}
\]

Bias correction
Simplest form of downscaling. Usually \(X\) are samples from a climate model and \(y\) are observations. \[
\begin{aligned}
\text{bias} &= \mathbb{E}[X] - \mathbb{E}[y] \\
\hat{y} &= X - \text{bias}
\end{aligned}
\]







